Issue: 
had a issue trying to setup passwords for the employees
Problem:
The password did not meet the domain password policy requirements (complexity rules).
Solution:
Updated the password to meet the policy requirements:
Minimum length
Included uppercase and lowercase letters
Included numbers and special characters

Example of valid password:
P@ssw0rd123!

Lesson Learned:
Active Directory enforces password policies set through Group Policy, so all user passwords must meet complexity requirements.

Issue: Organizing Shared Folders into a Single Directory
Problem:
Initially created separate folders (Sales, HR, IT) directly in the C:\ drive, which made the structure disorganized.
Cause:
Folders were created individually without planning a centralized directory structure.
Solution:
Created a parent folder (C:\Company Shares) and moved all department folders (Sales, HR, IT) inside it.
Final Structure:
C:\Company Shares
- Sales
- HR
- IT
Lesson Learned:
Using a centralized directory structure improves organization, scalability, and reflects real-world file server design.
Impact:
This structure makes it easier to manage permissions, locate resources, and maintain consistency across departments.
